Important Interview Questions

What is Git?
Git is a Version Control System used to track code changes and maintain version history.

What is GitHub?
GitHub is a cloud-based platform used to host and share Git repositories.

Difference Between Git and GitHub

Git:
- Version Control System
- Works locally

GitHub:
- Cloud platform
- Hosts remote repositories

What is a Repository?
A repository is a storage location where project files and version history are maintained.

What is a Commit?
A commit is a snapshot of the project at a particular point in time.

Command:
git commit -m "message"

What is Push?
Push sends committed changes from Local Repository to GitHub.

Command:
git push origin main

What is Pull?
Pull downloads the latest changes from GitHub to the local machine.

Command:
git pull

What is Clone?
Clone creates a copy of an existing remote repository on the local machine.

Command:
git clone <repository-url>

What is the Staging Area?
The staging area is an intermediate area where files are prepared before committing.

What Does git add Do?
It moves files from the Working Directory to the Staging Area.

How Do You Check Repository Status?
git status

How Do You View Commit History?
git log
or
git log --oneline

